    "summary": "The Corinthian War (395–387 BC) was a conflict pitting Sparta against a coalition of former allies — Corinth, Argos, Thebes, and Athens — along with Persia, which had reversed course from supporting Sparta during the [[event:1010|Peloponnesian War]] and now funded the anti-Spartan coalition to check Spartan power in Asia Minor. The war exposed Sparta's vulnerability as a hegemonic power unable to maintain the alliances that had won it the Peloponnesian War.\n\nDespite several Spartan land victories, including the battles of Nemea and Coronea in 394 BC, the Spartan fleet was destroyed by an Athenian admiral — Conon, commanding a Persian-financed fleet — at the Battle of Cnidus in 394 BC. Athens used Persian subsidies to rebuild its Long Walls, demolished after 404 BC. Ultimately Persia brokered the settlement: the King's Peace (also called the Peace of Antalcidas) of 387 BC returned Ionian Greek cities to Persian control while granting autonomy to all Greek cities. Sparta, tasked with enforcing these provisions, used them to break up coalitions it found threatening — revealing that Greek freedom had become a tool of great-power diplomacy rather than a genuine principle.",
